          explanation: 'This is a consequence of the equilibrium condition. If two non-parallel forces intersect at a point, their resultant also passes through that point. For the third force to create zero net moment about that intersection point, it must also pass through it (otherwise it would create an unbalanced moment). This principle is useful for checking equilibrium conditions and for solving three-force member problems. Note: this applies only to non-parallel forces — parallel forces in equilibrium do not share a common intersection.',
