          explanation: 'For the blocks to move together, two conditions must hold: (1) the friction between the floor and B must be overcome (this is the driving condition), and (2) the acceleration must not exceed what friction between A and B can provide to A. If they move together, acceleration a = (P - μ₂(m_A + m_B)g)/(m_A + m_B). For block A: μ₁m_Ag ≥ m_A × a. Solving: P ≤ μ₁m_Ag + μ₂(m_A + m_B)g... Actually the maximum P for which they move together is found by requiring that the friction on A (from B) can provide A the needed acceleration. This is a classic stacked-block friction problem that tests understanding of Newton\'s laws and friction simultaneously.',
