          explanation: 'The moment of inertia depends on how far material is from the neutral axis (I involves y² in the integral). An I-beam places most material in the flanges, far from the neutral axis, maximizing I for a given cross-sectional area. The web is thin because material near the neutral axis contributes little to I. A thin-walled tube is excellent for torsion but not optimal for single-axis bending. A solid circle wastes material near the center. This is why I-beams are the standard for beam design — the shape is literally optimized for bending efficiency.',
